Why this directory is GPLv2
---------------------------
The `doom` cog statically links the vendored `doomgeneric` C engine
(vendor/doomgeneric/), which is a derivative of id Software's original
DOOM source release. That source is licensed under GPLv2. Linking it
into the cog binary makes the resulting binary a derivative work, so the
whole cog (the Rust wrapper + the linked C engine) must be distributed
under GPLv2-compatible terms. See:

  * vendor/doomgeneric/LICENSE        (GPLv2, the engine's license)
  * vendor/doomgeneric/README         (origin: github.com/ozkl/doomgeneric)
  * ./LICENSE                          (full GPLv2 text, governing this cog)
  * Cargo.toml `license = "GPL-2.0-or-later"`

Scope
-----
ONLY the `src/cogs/doom/` directory is GPLv2. Every other cog and the
repository root remain MIT (see the repo-root LICENSE). Nothing in this
directory relicenses or "infects" the rest of the repo — GPL applies to
this derivative work, which is self-contained here.

Game data (no DOOM assets shipped)
----------------------------------
This cog vendors only the doomgeneric *engine* source — it ships NO DOOM
game data (no commercial or shareware WAD). At runtime it uses the
freely-redistributable FreeDoom IWAD (`freedoom1.wad`), declared as an
asset in cog.toml and fetched at install time. FreeDoom is distributed
under a BSD-3-Clause license by the Freedoom project
(https://freedoom.github.io/). FreeDoom's own license terms accompany
the WAD; it is not vendored in this repository.

For maintainers
---------------
Please confirm you accept a GPLv2 subdirectory living inside this
otherwise-MIT repository. If that is not acceptable, the alternative is
to host the doom cog in a separate repository and reference it from the
registry — but vendoring keeps the PR self-contained and CI green.
